This is a true edge case that came from bug 319123. The basic problem is the construct:

// Document 1
document.write(Foo!)

// document2.js
document.close()

Before my fix for bug 319123 we used to not really respect the close() call and actually leak the parser and all of the related stuff. Now we terminate the parser but that means that we lose the Foo!. IE seems to only respect the document.close after the document.write is done (i.e. a second document.write() after the one that closes the document actually starts a new document). I'm not sure what IE does with other s after the document.close though.

